summary: This is an email chain between U.S. Attorney's Office (SDNY) staff regarding the logistics of picking up a signed 6(e) order from Judge Alison Nathan's chambers. The order pertains to the Epstein case, and the emails discuss whether a magistrate judge's order is sufficient or if it needed to go to a district judge.

persons.name: Judge Nathan
persons.context: Judge Nathan is the judge who signed the 6(e) order in the Epstein case, and her clerk notified the U.S. Attorney's Office that the order was ready for pickup.

events.title: 6(e) Order Signed by Judge Nathan
events.description: Judge Alison Nathan signed a 6(e) order in the Epstein case, and her clerk notified the U.S. Attorney's Office that it was ready to be picked up from her chambers.

keyFacts: A 6(e) order related to the Epstein case was signed by U.S. District Judge Alison Nathan on or before January 31, 2020.
The U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York (SDNY) was coordinating the pickup of the signed order from Judge Nathan's chambers.
There was internal discussion among prosecutors about whether a magistrate judge's order was sufficient or if it needed to be signed by a district judge, referencing a prior order.
The email chain shows ongoing legal procedural activity in the Epstein case in early 2020, after Epstein's death in August 2019.
